Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

understand publishing as a process of releasing research outputs;
explain how persistent identifiers support credit, linkage, and traceability;
prepare data, code, and documentation for responsible reuse;
distinguish sharing from enabling reuse;
recognise how publishing choices affect reproducibility and sustainability.

This chapter builds on Chapter 2 — FAIR basics, Chapter 8 — Responsible research: roles, decisions, and accountability, and Chapter 9 — Automation & simple workflows.







Responsible publishing builds on responsible research



This chapter assumes the principles established in Chapter 8: ethical, legal, and contractual constraints on sharing should be explicit, justified, and documented.
Where outputs cannot be fully open, responsible publishing still requires clear metadata, documented access routes, and appropriate licensing for what can be shared.

Publishing beyond the paper
Research outputs extend beyond journal articles. They may include:

datasets and metadata;
analysis code and workflows;
protocols and documentation;
figures, tables, and derived materials;
preprints and other early research outputs.

Publishing these outputs supports transparency, enables reuse, and ensures appropriate attribution.







Responsible publishing sits on responsible research practice



This chapter assumes the principles in Chapter 8 (Responsible & sustainable research):
constraints on sharing should be justified, documented, and revisited, and restricted outputs can still be FAIR through metadata, documentation, and clear access conditions.

Publishing as release management
Publishing can be understood as the release of a research object.
A release typically involves:

freezing a version;
documenting scope, assumptions, and limitations;
assigning a persistent identifier;
specifying access conditions and licences.

Thinking in terms of releases supports clarity, traceability, and defensibility, particularly where outputs evolve over time.

Preprints as early dissemination
Preprints are public versions of research outputs shared prior to formal peer review. They support early dissemination, transparency, and feedback, and are now widely used in health and population research.
Preprints should be understood as a stage in the publishing lifecycle, not a replacement for peer-reviewed publication.
Used appropriately, preprints can:

make findings visible earlier;
establish precedence and credit;
invite methodological and substantive feedback.

However, preprints:

have not undergone peer review;
may change substantially before journal publication;
should be interpreted with appropriate caution, particularly for policy- or clinically relevant findings.

Good practice includes clearly labelling outputs as preprints and linking them to subsequent accepted or published versions where available.

Context is part of the output
Reuse depends on context.
Good publishing practice includes documenting:

analytical assumptions and decisions;
known limitations and sources of uncertainty;
constraints on interpretation or reuse;
relationships between outputs (data, code, documentation, publications).

Providing context reduces misinterpretation and inappropriate reuse. This includes structured metadata that supports discovery and interpretation, even when access to the underlying data is restricted.

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
In practice, preparing outputs often involves:

deciding early which outputs will be released and when;
using repositories that issue DOIs;
linking outputs consistently via ORCID;
choosing and recording an appropriate licence for each output;
documenting scope, assumptions, and reuse conditions.

These steps support visibility, credit, and robustness.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain why openness and reproducibility are now core expectations in research;
distinguish between openness, transparency, and reproducibility in practical terms;
recognise common sources of irreproducibility in everyday research workflows;
understand how open practices reduce research risk, inefficiency, and avoidable error;
see how the principles introduced here translate into concrete practices covered in later modules.

This module sets the conceptual foundation for the rest of the course. The next module moves from why openness matters to how to describe and structure outputs so they remain usable over time (Chapter 2: FAIR basics).

Where irreproducibility comes from (in normal workflows)
Irreproducibility is usually not caused by misconduct. More commonly it arises from routine workflow issues, including:

manual data cleaning or analysis steps that are not recorded;
unclear file organisation, naming, or versioning;
results generated interactively without a saved script or pipeline;
missing information about software environments or dependencies;
loss of project memory when staff or students move on.

These problems tend to surface late (submission, peer review, audit, or handover), when they are most expensive to fix.

What you will do in later modules
This course focuses on practical steps that reduce risk and increase continuity, including:

structuring data and materials for reuse (Chapter 2: FAIR basics);
organising projects so work remains legible and maintainable;
documenting decisions and workflows so results can be understood and defended;
improving code quality and reducing manual steps where appropriate;
preparing outputs for sharing, archiving, and attribution.

You are not expected to adopt everything at once. The course is designed to support incremental improvement.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain what the FAIR principles are and how they work in practice;
distinguish FAIR from openness, documentation, and data management planning;
understand what Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable mean conceptually;
recognise how FAIR applies to data, code, and other research outputs;
understand where FAIR principles are implemented later in the research workflow.

This module builds on the motivation introduced in Chapter 1 – Why Open?. It introduces FAIR as a set of design principles for research outputs, not as a checklist or compliance exercise.

Interoperable: how outputs can be interpreted correctly
Interoperable means that outputs can be understood and used correctly in different contexts, systems, or tools.
This is supported by:

standard or widely used file formats;
consistent variable naming and coding;
use of shared vocabularies or conventions where appropriate;
clear documentation of transformations and assumptions.

Interoperability reduces the risk of misinterpretation when data or code move between people, teams, or software environments.

Reusable: how outputs can be used again
Reusable means that outputs can be used again for future research, whether by others or by your future self.
Reusability depends on:

sufficient contextual information to interpret the output;
clear licensing and reuse conditions;
versioning and provenance information;
documentation of limitations, assumptions, and constraints.

Reusability is not about guaranteeing reuse; it is about making reuse possible and responsible.

FAIR applies to more than datasets
FAIR principles apply to:

datasets and associated metadata;
analysis code and scripts;
protocols, analysis plans, and workflows;
documentation capturing decisions and provenance.

Applying FAIR principles to code and documentation often delivers the greatest immediate gains in reproducibility and project continuity.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain why project organisation is central to reproducibility and continuity;
describe how metadata, roles, and conventions support collaboration;
apply proportionate principles for organisation, versioning, and continuity;
understand how project organisation underpins documentation, code, and automation;
locate UCL-supported tools and templates relevant to project organisation.

This module builds on the FAIR principles introduced in Chapter 2: FAIR basics and focuses on how projects are structured and managed over time.
All copy-ready templates and concrete examples are provided centrally in the Resources and Further Reading chapter.

Why project organisation matters
Many reproducibility problems arise not from technical complexity, but from poorly organised projects. As projects grow, involve multiple contributors, or span years, it becomes increasingly difficult to track what was done, why it was done, and by whom. This chapter does not teach general project management skills; it focuses on organisational practices that directly support reproducibility, governance, and long-term continuity.
Effective project organisation supports1:

continuity when team members join or leave;
transparent decision making;
efficient collaboration across roles and disciplines;
traceability of changes and outputs.

These benefits are particularly important in research, where projects often involve multiple data types, governance requirements, and extended timelines.

Metadata about the project
A project is more than a collection of files. Treat project-level metadata as a first-class research output. This metadata is distinct from dataset-level metadata (covered in Chapter 5), and exists to make the project itself legible.
At a minimum, this includes:

a brief description of purpose and scope;
the outputs the project will generate and how they are identified (e.g. PIDs);
conventions for naming, versioning, and access;
roles and responsibilities for key tasks.

A short project README or charter at the top level of your repository or shared drive improves discoverability, onboarding, and continuity.
A minimum README template is provided in Resources and Further Reading.

Structuring the project
Well-organised projects tend to share common structural features, regardless of discipline or tools:

a clear top-level project boundary;
separation of raw data, derived data, analysis code, and outputs;
a visible project metadata file (e.g. README);
predictable locations for documentation and logs.

Structure should prioritise legibility for someone unfamiliar with the project, including reviewers and your future self.
Rather than inventing bespoke layouts, this course encourages starting from a simple baseline structure and adapting it as needed.
A canonical folder structure and guidance on its intended use are provided in the Resources and Further Reading chapter.

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
For early career researchers, proportionate project organisation often means:

writing a project README at the outset;
agreeing simple versioning conventions with collaborators;
maintaining a short decision log alongside active work;
keeping tasks, roles, and responsibilities visible to the team.

These steps support transparent progress without requiring heavy infrastructure.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain the purpose of a Data Management Plan beyond funder compliance;
recognise a DMP as a living record of decisions;
distinguish data description from data governance;
identify proportionate planning actions for different data types;
locate UCL guidance, templates, and support for DMPs.

This module builds on FAIR principles Chapter 2: FAIR basics and project organisation Chapter 3 - Project organisation and continuity. It prepares you for practical data handling and documentation in later chapters. At UCL, DMPs are structured around six core areas: data collection, storage and security, archiving and preservation, discovery and access, metadata, and roles and responsibilities.
This chapter focuses on what a DMP must commit to and how assessors interpret it. Chapters 5–7 cover implementation in practice (data organisation, documentation, and code), and Chapter 9 covers automation and workflows.

DMPs as decision records
Good DMPs document decisions made under uncertainty, including:

what will happen if data cannot be shared openly;
how access will be managed under different scenarios;
who is responsible for data stewardship over time;
how data will be discovered, accessed, or requested, including where metadata will remain available even when access is restricted.

Updating a DMP is good practice, not a failure of planning.

What assessors look for in a good DMP
When reviewing a Data Management Plan, assessors are not looking for technical detail for its own sake. Instead, they look for evidence that data management has been thought through, is feasible, and is proportionate to the project context.
Strong DMPs typically demonstrate:

clarity about what data will be created or used;
realistic plans for documentation, storage, and preservation;
awareness of ethical, legal, and contractual constraints;
alignment between stated plans and the way the project is organised in practice;
named responsibility for data stewardship during the project and after staff or funding end.

Vague or generic statements are a common reason for weak DMP assessments.

DMP support at UCL
UCL provides:

an institutional DMP template;
Research Data Management guidance;
support via Library Services and specialist teams.

Relevant links, templates, and contacts are collated in the Resources and Further Reading chapter (see Data Management Plans in Resources) to keep this module focused on principles rather than policy detail.

Practical prompts when drafting a DMP
In practice, effective DMPs often make the following points explicit:

what data types, formats, and volumes are in scope (and what is out of scope);
likely access and sharing constraints, and how these will be managed;
who is responsible for data stewardship during the project and after staff turnover;
when the DMP will be reviewed and updated (e.g., start-up, mid-project, pre-publication, project end).

These prompts support continuity and reduce last-minute compliance work.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain why data organisation is central to reproducibility and reuse;
distinguish raw, cleaned, and derived data in practice;
understand data provenance and why it matters;
document missingness, exclusions, and transformations proportionately;
locate minimum standards, examples, and templates for organised data.

This module builds on data planning Chapter 4 — Data Management Plans (UCL) and supports later modules on documentation, code, automation, and publishing.
All concrete examples, templates, and minimum-standard artefacts are provided centrally in the Resources and Further Reading chapter.

Why data organisation matters
Poorly organised data are difficult to understand, validate, or reuse—even by the original researcher. Organisation choices made early in a project shape how easily analyses can be checked, rerun, or extended later.
Good data organisation:

reduces ambiguity about what files represent;
preserves provenance and interpretability;
supports efficient analysis and collaboration;
reduces the risk of accidental data loss or misuse.

These benefits apply regardless of whether data can ultimately be shared openly.

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
In practice, proportionate data organisation often involves:

freezing raw data early and working on copies;
creating a short data dictionary alongside cleaning;
documenting transformations as they occur, not retrospectively;
agreeing naming and versioning conventions within the team.

These steps scale from individual projects to large collaborations.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain why documentation is central to reproducibility and continuity;
distinguish between different types of research documentation;
decide when to use READMEs, ELNs, SOPs, or other formats;
recognise documentation as a tool for collaboration and handover;
apply proportionate documentation practices in everyday workflows.

This module builds on Chapter 3 - Project organisation and continuity and [Chapter 5 - Organising and tidying data] (05-organise-tidy.qmd). It supports later modules on code, automation, and publishing.

Documentation as decision capture
Good documentation records not only what was done, but why it was done.
Documentation records analytical judgement, not just procedure. This includes coding decisions, exclusions, parameter choices, and deviations from plans, particularly in exploratory or qualitative work. Good documentation should allow an independent researcher to understand what was done, why it was done, and under what constraints. Documentation is evidence, not memory: it should be attributable, legible, contemporaneous, and retrievable.
This includes:

analytical choices and assumptions;
changes to protocols or plans;
reasons for exclusions or deviations;
trade-offs made under constraints.

Capturing decisions supports transparency and reduces reliance on memory.
Responsibility for maintaining documentation should be explicit and shared across teams; roles and institutional responsibilities are discussed in Chapter 8.






Documenting PPIE decisions



Record:

who was involved and in what capacity;
which stages of the research they informed;
how input influenced decisions (or why it did not);
any constraints on sharing or reuse arising from PPIE.

Using ELNs effectively
ELNs are most useful for recording:

what was attempted and what happened;
decisions made during data collection or analysis;
deviations from plans or protocols.

ELNs are not well suited for:

long-term instructions (use SOPs);
final project summaries (use READMEs);
storing large data files.

Keeping ELNs focused improves their value for review and handover.

Documentation and collaboration
Documentation is a shared resource. Clear, accessible documentation:

supports onboarding of new team members;
reduces reliance on informal knowledge;
improves equity by making expectations explicit;
supports offboarding and long-term continuity.

These benefits are particularly important in interdisciplinary and distributed teams.






Documenting AI-assisted work



If AI tools are used for coding, data cleaning, or analysis, record:

the tool and version;
the purpose (e.g. refactoring, summarisation, feature generation);
human review and validation steps;
known limitations or non-determinism.

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
In practice, proportionate documentation often involves:

maintaining a short project README;
recording key decisions in an ELN or decision log;
creating SOPs only for tasks that are repeated;
reviewing documentation at project milestones.

Documentation should evolve with the project.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain why code quality and documentation underpin reproducibility and defensibility;
recognise the role of testing in reliable research workflows;
understand how inefficient code affects reproducibility and sustainability;
apply proportionate “green coding” practices in research contexts;
identify practical steps to reduce unnecessary computation.

This module builds on Chapter 6 — Documentation, ELNs & SOPs and prepares you for automation and workflows in Chapter 9 — Automation & simple workflows.

Why code quality matters in research
In research contexts, code quality is not about elegance or performance alone. It is about whether results can be:

regenerated reliably;
inspected and reviewed;
adapted or extended by others (including your future self).

Poor-quality code increases the risk of silent errors, irreproducible results, and excessive rework.

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
Proportionate steps for most research projects include:

writing scripts so they can be run end-to-end;
adding basic checks or tests for key assumptions;
avoiding unnecessary recomputation during exploration;
documenting when and why full reruns are required.

More advanced optimisation is context-dependent and not always necessary.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain responsibility as an ongoing research practice;
recognise ethical, legal, and governance considerations in everyday workflows;
identify and articulate roles and responsibilities within a research project;
document constraints, decisions, and trade-offs transparently;
link responsibility to decisions about sharing, restriction, and reuse.

This module builds on Chapter 7 — Code quality & testing and informs later decisions about Chapter 10 — Publishing, PIDs & preparing for reuse.

Roles, responsibilities, and accountability
Responsibility in research is distributed.
Projects involve multiple roles, which may overlap and change over time. Examples include:

principal investigator or project lead;
supervisors and advisory roles;
analysts and data stewards;
collaborators and external partners;
institutional approvers and governance bodies.

Unclear or assumed responsibilities are a common source of risk. When roles are not explicit, decisions may be delayed, duplicated, or left undocumented.
Responsible research therefore requires:

identifying who is responsible for key decisions;
recognising where responsibilities overlap;
recording how decisions are made and by whom.

This is particularly important for:

data access and governance;
ethics and regulatory approvals;
analytical choices and exclusions;
decisions about sharing, restriction, and reuse.

Responsibility is not about assigning blame. It is about ensuring that accountability is visible, supported, and reviewable.

Institutional support and escalation routes
Responsibility is supported by institutional infrastructure.
At UCL, guidance and support are available for:

research ethics and governance;
data protection and information security;
research integrity and responsible conduct;
data management, sharing, and preservation.

Knowing when and where to seek advice is itself a responsible practice.
Relevant training, policies, and support routes are collated in the Resources and Further Reading.

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
For early-career researchers, proportionate responsible practice often involves:

clarifying roles and expectations early in a project;
documenting constraints and trade-offs rather than hiding them;
recording decisions as they are made, not retrospectively;
seeking advice when boundaries or responsibilities are unclear.

Responsibility is a shared, supported practice — not an individual burden.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

explain why automation supports reproducibility and efficiency;
recognise which steps benefit most from automation;
understand automation as dependency management;
link automation to reduced compute waste and sustainability;
apply proportionate automation in research workflows.

This module builds on Chapter 7 — Code quality & testing and Chapter 8 — Responsible research: roles, decisions, and accountability. It prepares you for Chapter 10 — Publishing, PIDs & preparing for reuse.

Automation as dependency management
At its core, automation is about dependencies:

which files or datasets are inputs;
which scripts transform them;
which outputs depend on which steps.

When dependencies are explicit, workflows can:

rerun only what has changed;
avoid accidental full reprocessing;
make provenance easier to inspect and explain.

Simple automation relies on good foundations: clear folder structure, stable file naming, versioning, and separation of raw and derived data, as introduced in Chapter 5 — Organising and tidying data.

Transparency and automation
Automated workflows support transparency by:

documenting execution order implicitly;
making assumptions and dependencies explicit;
producing consistent, traceable outputs.

Automation complements documentation — it does not replace it. Clear READMEs, comments, and decision logs remain essential (see Chapter 6).

Practical guidance for ECR workflows
For most research projects, proportionate automation involves:

writing scripts that can be run from top to bottom;
avoiding manual edits to generated files;
recording when and why full reruns are required;
adding automation incrementally as projects mature.

You do not need complex tools to gain most of the benefits. Consistency and clarity matter more than sophistication.
Examples, tools, and further guidance are collated in the Resources and Further Reading chapter.

Learning objectives
By the end of this module, you should be able to:

reflect on what proportionate open and reproducible practice looks like;
identify which practices matter most in your own context;
recognise reproducibility as a form of risk reduction;
know where to go next for tools, guidance, and support.

This module consolidates the ideas introduced across Modules 1–10 and points to resources for continued learning and application.

What “good enough” looks like
Reproducibility is incremental.
What is appropriate depends on:

project scale and risk;
data sensitivity and governance;
team size and turnover;
available time and resources.

Good practice means making choices explicit and defensible—not maximising openness at any cost.

Reproducibility as risk reduction
Many open research practices function as risk management:

documentation reduces reliance on memory;
versioning reduces accidental loss;
automation reduces silent errors;
testing reduces rework;
clear publishing reduces misinterpretation.

Seen this way, reproducibility supports both research quality and researcher wellbeing.

Where to go next
Depending on your needs, next steps may include:

consulting the Resources and Further Reading chapter;
engaging with UCL support services for data, ethics, and open access;
attending further training or workshops.

Learning and improvement are ongoing processes.

Applying this in your own work
A practical way forward is to:

choose one or two practices to strengthen in your next project;
revisit them at key project milestones;
build habits gradually rather than all at once.

Small, consistent improvements deliver the greatest benefit.
